            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I have a branch that adds inbound kitty graphics protocol handling to `:terminal`. It's built on top of #39496 and makes use of the buffer-local api to insert images into the terminal buffer that persist through scrolling and other things just like a normal buffer. This involves leveraging the `TermRequest`  autocmd to grab the kitty graphics protocol, parse it, and translate it into calls to `vim.ui.img.set()` and `vim.ui.img.del()`.\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/91a3c94d-f709-4197-b046-6c4c2c2dc6bb\n\nThere are some limitations I hit so far that we'd need to figure out, @justinmk \n\n1. The kitty graphics protocol supports RGB and RGBA alongside PNG. The workaround I did for now is to translate RGB/RGBA into a PNG, which is fairly easy to do in Lua, and then pass it to `vim.ui.img.set()`. Using something like `chafa`, it shared the image data as RGBA, so without this the calls to `vim.ui.img.set()` weren't working.\n2. There seems to be a problem with `on_apc`/`on_osc`/`on_dcs` in `src/nvim/terminal.c` returning early whenever vterm delivers a fragment with `frag.len == 0`. Chafa sent over 1500 chunked escape sequences, which resulted in vterm splitting a handful of the sequences where the body and the trailing `final` flag arrive in separate fragments, which with the early exit caused some of the chunks to get dropped. I added a fix for that, but not sure if there are any other consequences of it. Could spin that up as a separate PR to be reviewed.\n3. Some tools check available terminal sizes before determining which API to call. When using `yazi`, it wouldn't use the kitty protocol even when I had `:terminal` support responding to csi 14t and csi 16t. I think this is because it may use `ioctl(TIOCGWINSZ)` instead, and if I'm not mistaken we set `ws_xpixel` and `ws_ypixel` to 0. @tbung was exploring in this space, maybe?",
